---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Editorial Team | truckaccidentcalc.com';
const description = 'Meet the editorial team behind truckaccidentcalc.com — credentials, areas of focus, and how we keep content current and accurate.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>truckaccidentcalc.com is reviewed by a small editorial team with professional experience in personal injury and transportation law. We are not attorneys; we don't represent clients. We do read the federal regulations, the case-valuation handbooks, and the verdict reporters so that our content reflects how the practice actually works rather than how it's marketed.</p>

  <h2>Commercial Trucking Claims</h2>
  <p><strong>Credentials:</strong> Paralegals in transportation litigation, with prior work supporting plaintiff-side commercial vehicle cases.</p>
  <p><strong>Coverage areas:</strong> FMCSA compliance and how it intersects with liability; case valuation framework; settlement negotiation strategy; identification of all potentially liable parties (driver, carrier, broker, shipper, loader, manufacturer); analysis of electronic logging device and dashcam evidence.</p>
  <p><strong>Editorial role:</strong> Reviews every published page on the site, signs off on the methodology, and approves any change to the calculator's formulas or severity tiers.</p>

  <h2>DOT and FMCSA Compliance</h2>
  <p><strong>Credentials:</strong> Paralegals in regulatory matters, with backgrounds in carrier compliance review and DOT audit support.</p>
  <p><strong>Coverage areas:</strong> Hours-of-service rules; driver qualification files; medical certification; drug-and-alcohol testing requirements; cargo securement standards; insurance minimums; how FMCSA violations affect liability in private litigation.</p>
  <p><strong>Editorial role:</strong> Researches and drafts regulatory and compliance pieces; flags rule changes (annual updates to FMCSA minimum coverage, hours-of-service revisions, exempt commodity changes) so methodology and guides stay current.</p>

  <h2>Editorial process</h2>
  <p>Pages move through draft &rarr; technical review &rarr; editorial review &rarr; publication. Technical review checks the math, the cited regulations, and any state-specific claims. Editorial review checks clarity, structure, and that the page actually answers the question someone would have when they landed on it. Pages are dated; substantive updates are noted in a revision line at the top of the page.</p>

  <p>Mistakes happen. If you find one, send a correction via the <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> and we'll fix it &mdash; if substantive, we add a correction note at the top of the page.</p>

  <h2>What we don't do</h2>
  <p>We don't provide legal advice on specific cases, and our editorial content isn't for sale — no attorney pays for coverage or a favorable mention in our guides. Separately, the case-review form on our homepage is a disclosed paid referral: submitting it shares your information with attorneys who may compensate The Click Lab Agency LLC for the introduction. See our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for details. Revenue also comes from display advertising via Google AdSense.</p>

  <p>If you need legal advice on your specific situation, find a personal injury attorney licensed in your state. Your state bar's lawyer referral service or the trial lawyers' association in your state can help you get started.</p>
</BaseLayout>
